1.2 Core Proposition: Myth as Raw Data of Cognitive Encoding

This model positions myth as: real physical observational data, encoded through the cognitive framework of the Stone Age. Ancient peoples did not fabricate celestial events; but they described what they saw using their only available cognitive tools—mythological language, hunting experience, and spatial analogies.

Thus, the value of myth lies not in providing precise numbers or geometric details, but in providing the sequential structure of events and qualitative descriptions of phenomena. Differences between civilisations (numbers, names, details) arise from stochastic deformation during encoding, not from the fiction of the events themselves.

