1.4 Visual Fingerprint Exclusion of Candidate Catastrophe Models

The model’s choice of “extremely close flyby of a super‑comet” as the physical prototype for global creation myths is not a theoretical preference, but is forced by the mythological data themselves. Below, we systematically compare all known astrophysical and geological catastrophe processes to show that only this scenario can simultaneously satisfy the four phenomenological constraints.

1.4.1 The Four Visual Features of Myths—Phenomenological Constraints

A systematic review of visual descriptions in global creation myths yields four transcultural common features:

Feature 1: All‑covering dome (“Chaos like a chicken egg”) — Myths do not describe a distant point or local fireball, but a surrounding, enveloping sky‑spanning phenomenon. The Chinese myth “Heaven and earth were chaotic like a chicken egg” is typical—chaos is likened to a closed, enveloping eggshell, not an open sky. This demands an extremely large angular diameter (>10°) for the catastrophe body, occupying a vast area from horizon to zenith.
Feature 2: Vertical light pillar (“Heavenly pillar”) — Many civilisations have a “heavenly pillar” or “world axis”—a luminous column extending vertically from the ground to the zenith. China’s “pillar breaks,” the Norse “World Tree,” and Greece’s “Atlas” all point to a pronounced vertical structure. This requires a light source with clear directional extension from near‑ground to high altitude.
Feature 3: Sequential falls (“Shooting the suns”) — The multiple suns do not disappear simultaneously, but are shot/fall one by one. China’s “Yi shot the ten suns, hitting nine,” and India’s “Indra kills Vritra” both show sequential disappearance. This requires multiple independent luminous bodies in the sky that vanish one after another within an observable time window.
Feature 4: Colourful canopy (“Five‑coloured stones to mend the sky”) — The sky changes colour described as “five colours,” not simple greyness—Chinese Nüwa “smelted five‑coloured stones to mend the azure sky.” This requires materials entering the atmosphere to excite multi‑wavelength visible emission, not merely produce grey dust.
