1.4.3 “Astronomical Fingerprint” Matching Argument

The above four constraints form a unique “astronomical fingerprint”—a combination of four features. Any candidate catastrophe model that claims to be the prototype must simultaneously produce all four.

The model’s argument is: Among all known astrophysical processes in the Solar System, only a super‑comet nucleus passing extremely close to the Roche limit can simultaneously generate the four visual features: all‑covering dome, vertical light pillar, sequential falls, and colourful canopy. Therefore, the mythological data themselves force the cometary scenario—this is a logical necessity of data constraint.

1.4.4 Methodological Significance: From “Decoding” to “Constraint”

The visual‑fingerprint exclusion analysis in §1.4 has deeper methodological meaning. It shows that myth, as cognitive‑encoding data, can not only be decoded but also can inversely constrain the construction of physical models. This answers the traditional criticism that “mythological evidence is too flexible”—when we treat the combination of visual features as strict constraints, myth becomes not “soft evidence that can explain anything,” but “hard constraints that exclude all other explanations.”

This methodological framework can be summarised as: Myths are not illustrations to “confirm” physical hypotheses, but filters to “select” them.

2. Celestial Mechanics Model: From Palaeo‑Moon to New Moon

2.1 Initial Conditions: Existence and Evidence for the Palaeo‑Moon

2.1.1 Origin of the Palaeo‑Moon—A Natural Explanation for the Orbital Gap Between Mars and Jupiter

The Solar System has an orbital gap of about 3.7 AU between Mars (≈1.5 AU) and Jupiter (≈5.2 AU). The standard model attributes this to Jupiter’s gravitational perturbations preventing planetesimal accretion.

This model proposes that one medium‑sized (diameter ≈1000‑2000 km) protoplanet was scattered into the inner Solar System by Jupiter‑Saturn gravitational resonance, and was subsequently captured by Earth’s gravity, becoming Earth’s original satellite—the Palaeo‑Moon.

Supporting evidence:

Differentiation evidence in the asteroid belt: Vesta (diam. 525 km) is fully differentiated, proving that large protoplanets capable of internal melting once existed there.
Earth’s exceptional lack of small moons: Mars has two small moons (Phobos, Deimos); Earth, being larger, has none—the most natural explanation is that it once had one, but it was removed or merged during a recent event.
