The Palaeo‑Moon’s apparent diameter was only 0.15°‑0.3° (human naked‑eye resolution ≈0.02°), resolvable as a disk, but incomparable to the “New Moon” (initial apparent diameter 4°‑10°) that appeared 30,000 years later. The fact that unequivocal depictions of a large satellite (Moon) in Late Palaeolithic cave art (≈40,000‑20,000 BP) are extremely rare and contested in dating—this archaeological observation is qualitatively consistent with the model’s prediction that the Palaeo‑Moon had only 30%‑60% of the modern Moon’s apparent diameter, making it too visually insignificant to be a cultural focus (see §5.2).

2.2 Trigger Event: Scholz’s Star Flyby and Cometary Debris Shower

In 2015, Mamajek et al. confirmed that Scholz’s Star (WISE J072003.20‑084651.2) flew through the Oort Cloud at a distance of 0.8 light‑years (52,000 AU) about 70,000 years ago. This event perturbed the inner Oort Cloud (≈2000‑5000 AU) icy body reservoir.

Key recognition: This was a cometary debris shower affecting the entire Solar System. The debris from the Oort Cloud did not fly only toward Earth, but spread throughout the Solar System. Jupiter, as the inner Solar System’s gravitational shield (Hill sphere radius ≈0.36 AU, gravitational cross‑section ≈125,000 times that of Earth), intercepted the vast majority. The comet nucleus captured by Earth and its subsequent debris were merely a small fraction of the survivors that crossed Jupiter’s defence line and reached the Earth‑Moon system.

