2.2.1 Physical Properties of the Comet Nucleus: The Three‑Layer Structure Model—The Mechanical Cornerstone of This Model

Oort Cloud bodies and inner Solar System rocky bodies have fundamental structural differences. The comet nucleus (diameter 4000‑5000 km) discussed in this model, before encountering Earth, had a clear three‑layer structure:

Outer layer (thick ice shell): Thickness ≈1000‑1500 km, density ≈0.9 g/cm³, composed of pure water ice, dry ice (CO₂), methane ice, and volatile organics. This is the main volumetric component.
Middle layer (ice‑dust transition zone): Thickness ≈500 km, mixed ice and solid particles, density transitioning to 1.0‑1.5 g/cm³.
Inner core (solid residue): Diameter ≈1500‑2500 km. This is the main body left after complete evaporation of the ice shell. It is not a dense rocky sphere, but a high‑porosity (30%‑50%), low‑density (1.0‑1.8 g/cm³), low‑cohesion (<1 kPa tensile strength) “rubble pile” aggregate, composed of early Solar System planetesimal debris (carbonaceous, silicate powders, organic aggregates) loosely accumulated under extremely low‑temperature vacuum conditions, never subjected to high‑temperature sintering or gravitational compaction. This model brackets specific mineralogy and relies only on its mechanical state—loose, compressible, with exponentially decaying shock waves.
Key physical implications of this structure (the model’s mechanical soul):

Capture probability greatly increased: Lower density means larger tidal radius and stronger tidal dissipation (viscoelastic ice deformation losses), making the otherwise measure‑zero three‑body capture physically possible.
Impact “cushioning” rather than rigid collision: When icy fragments impact the main nucleus, the target is the ice shell or underlying porous matrix. Shock waves decay exponentially in porous media, with energy absorbed by adiabatic compression of pores, grain friction, and fragmentation. This explains the “broad, shallow, flat‑bottomed, no central peak” morphology of mare basins.
Merger “embedding” rather than pulverisation: When the Palaeo‑Moon encounters the main nucleus, the dense rocky Palaeo‑Moon first hits the thick ice shell. Ice under high‑speed impact undergoes shock melting and vaporisation, absorbing most kinetic energy, allowing the Palaeo‑Moon to “melt through” the ice shell and embed, rather than catastrophic rigid‑body collision and fragmentation.
Sublimation‑driven orbital migration: The merged “big ice ball” continuously sublimates under heat, losing mass and pushing the orbit outward via angular momentum conservation (R ∝ 1/M², §2.8).
2.3 Phase 1: Close Flyby, Tidal Disruption, and Capture—The Physical Origin of “Opening Heaven and Earth”

2.3.1 Tidal Dissipation Capture Mechanism

Pure gravitational three‑body capture has measure‑zero in phase space. This model invokes tidal dissipation as the non‑conservative mechanism: when the comet nucleus (diameter 4000‑5000 km, mass ~10²³ kg, outer thick ice shell) flies past Earth on a hyperbolic orbit, if its perigee enters Earth’s Hill sphere (radius ≈1.5 million km), Earth’s tides cause significant dissipation inside the nucleus, converting orbital energy from positive (hyperbolic) to negative (elliptical), achieving capture.

Parameter range: initial relative velocity 10‑15 km/s; perigee geocentric distance 22,000‑32,000 km (surface altitude 15,000‑25,000 km); post‑capture orbit highly elliptical (perigee 22,000‑32,000 km, apogee 80,000‑150,000 km).

2.3.2 Tidal Disruption: The Physical Inevitability of the Roche Limit

This is the model’s most critical theoretical correction.

For a spherical body of density ρ<sub>c</sub> and radius R<sub>c</sub> at distance d from a planet of mass M<sub>E</sub>, the Roche limit where tidal force balances self‑gravity is:

For a fluid/no‑cohesion rubble‑pile structure (reasonable for a comet nucleus):

d<sub>Roche</sub> ≈ 2.44 × R<sub>E</sub> × ( ρ<sub>E</sub> / ρ<sub>c</sub> )<sup>1/3</sup>
where R<sub>E</sub> = 6371 km, ρ<sub>E</sub> = 5510 kg/m³.

Substituting ρ<sub>c</sub> = 1000‑1500 kg/m³:

ρ<sub>c</sub> = 1500 kg/m³: d<sub>Roche</sub> ≈ 2.44 × 6371 × (3.67)<sup>1/3</sup> ≈ 23,900 km
ρ<sub>c</sub> = 1000 kg/m³: d<sub>Roche</sub> ≈ 2.44 × 6371 × (5.51)<sup>1/3</sup> ≈ 27,500 km
The perigee geocentric distance in this model (22,000‑32,000 km) fully covers or even goes below the Roche limit interval (~24,000‑28,000 km).

Key conclusion: During the extremely close flyby, the comet nucleus is at or below its Roche limit. For a low‑density, no‑internal‑strength ice‑rock rubble pile, this means tidal disruption is a physical inevitability, not a chance event.

Physical picture of disruption: The side of the comet closer to Earth experiences a gravitational pull stronger than the far side by Δg ≈ 2 × (GM<sub>E</sub>/d³) × R<sub>c</sub>. For R<sub>c</sub> ≈ 2500 km, d ≈ 25,000 km, Δg ≈ 2 × (6.67×10⁻¹¹ × 5.97×10²⁴ / (2.5×10⁷)³) × 2.5×10⁶ ≈ 0.02 m/s². This tidal stretching acceleration exceeds the comet’s own surface gravity (g<sub>self</sub> ≈ G × M<sub>c</sub> / R<sub>c</sub>² ≈ 6.67×10⁻¹¹ × 10²³ / (2.5×10⁶)² ≈ 0.01 m/s²). Tide exceeds self‑gravity → disruption inevitable.

Disruption outcome: The nucleus is stretched and torn into 1 main nucleus (retaining most mass) and 5‑15 larger fragments (diameter 50‑200 km), plus numerous small pieces and icy debris. Fragments align along the flight direction as a “string of pearls,” size distribution following a collisional cascade power law (N(>D) ∝ D<sup>‑2.5</sup>).

This is fully analogous to the tidal disruption of Comet Shoemaker‑Levy 9 near Jupiter (Weaver et al., 1994). The difference is that Earth’s mass is much smaller, so the tidal gradient is weaker, yielding fewer fragments (SL9 produced 21) and a size distribution shifted toward larger fragments.

Improvement in capture probability: In the fragmented swarm, each fragment has its own orbital energy. The probability of capturing a single giant body is extremely low, but capturing a swarm is much higher—once the main nucleus is bound by tidal dissipation, its associated fragments, having small velocity dispersion, are automatically bound by Earth’s gravity. This fundamentally solves the physical difficulty that “capture of a single giant comet has near‑zero probability.”

2.3.3 Visual Physics of “Opening Heaven and Earth” and Super‑Tides

The extremely close flyby (altitude 15,000‑25,000 km) gives the 5000‑km‑diameter main nucleus an angular diameter of 10°‑15°, occupying most of the sky—the physical realisation of “Feature 1: all‑covering dome” (§1.4). Its coma and vapour enshroud the sky, creating the visual experience of “heaven and earth chaotic like a chicken egg”—a precise, transcultural record of retinal images.

Simultaneously, the coma and tail form a vertical luminous pillar extending from horizon to zenith outside the atmosphere—the physical realisation of “Feature 2: vertical pillar” (§1.4), recorded by ancients as the “heavenly pillar.” This pillar was not a structural support but a glowing column covering half the sky, stretching from ground to zenith.

Visual decoding of “Kai Tian” (Opening Heaven): The Chinese word “开辟” (kāi pì) carries the dual meaning of “split open” and “tear apart.” The model points out that this is not an abstract metaphor for cosmic origin, but a real‑time naked‑eye record of the physical dynamic process of the comet nucleus undergoing tidal disruption below the Roche limit.

When the tidal tensile stress described in §2.3.2 exceeds the comet’s self‑gravity, a complete dome‑shaped body thousands of kilometres across is literally “torn apart” on the spot by Earth’s gravitational gradient within hours to days—the main body splits into 1 main nucleus and 5‑15 fragments aligned like a string of pearls. This “tearing” dynamic occurs outside the atmosphere, but due to the huge angular area and cometary reflection, it is clearly visible to the naked eye during daytime or twilight.

The ancients witnessed a complete, sky‑spanning “celestial canopy” entity being cleaved into multiple independent luminous bodies before their eyes. This incomprehensible visual spectacle was encoded as “Opening Heaven”—the sky itself was split open.

Correspondingly, “Pi Di” (Splitting Earth) encodes the seismic shaking, super‑tides, and inundation caused by the gravitational effects of the tidal forces—the earth also “cracked” and “overturned.” Together they form the complete narrative of “Opening Heaven and Splitting Earth”: the sky split above, the ground sank below.

Origin of super‑tides: The main nucleus has mass ~10²³ kg (comparable to the Moon) and flies past Earth at a perigee altitude of only 15,000‑25,000 km. According to Newton’s law of gravitation, tidal force is proportional to the mass of the perturber and inversely proportional to the cube of distance: F<sub>tide</sub> ∝ M<sub>comet</sub> / R³. At R = 20,000 km, the tide from the main nucleus is about (384,000/20,000)³ = 19.2³ ≈ 7,077 times that of the present Moon. Even accounting for mass differences (comparable), the tidal force is thousands of times stronger.

This means: daily tidal waves of hundreds to thousands of metres, periodic complete inundation of coastal lands, elastic deformation of the crust (triggering arc volcanism and earthquakes)—“the four pillars collapsed, the nine provinces split,” “the heavenly pillar broke, the earth’s tethers snapped.”

Key clarification: The super‑tides were caused directly by the gravitational effect of the large comet nucleus itself during its extremely close flyby, independent of subsequent impact rainfall. Flooding from rain and flooding from tides were superimposed, but tides were the dominant factor—the inverse‑cube distance dependence makes this effect overwhelming.

2.3.4 Visual Decoding of “The Sky Leans to the Northwest”

“The sky leans to the northwest” is not a physical deflection of Earth’s rotation axis, but a geometric perspective effect produced by the super‑giant comet nucleus moving in near‑Earth space. When the nucleus (apparent diameter 10°‑15°, occupying most of the sky) reaches near perigee during its close flyby, if its azimuth is to the northwest of the observer (East Asia), a glowing giant dome‑shaped body hangs between the northwestern horizon and the zenith.

Because the body’s angular scale far exceeds the human visual system’s routine recognition of a “single flying object,” the observer cannot identify it as “a sphere coming from the northwest,” but can only perceive that: the northwestern sky itself is deforming, “tilting” or “collapsing” toward the earth. As Earth rotates and the comet moves along its orbit, this huge luminous structure slowly shifts southeastward, visually appearing as if the entire sky frame is tilting and crumbling toward the northwest.

This experience was precisely encoded as “The sky leans to the northwest, therefore the sun, moon, and stars move” — here “the sun, moon, and stars move” does not mean physical displacement of stars in space, but means: when that giant object occupying most of the sky moves, its relative positions with the Sun, Moon, and other visible bodies undergo violent visual reorganisation, temporarily disrupting the entire sense of orientation of the starry background.

2.4 Phase 2: “Multiple Suns in the Sky” and Frontal Impacts—Orbital Rendezvous of Fragments

2.4.1 Natural Visual Selection and the Number of “Suns”

The size distribution in the fragment swarm follows a power law (N(>D) ∝ D<sup>‑2.5</sup>). The number of fragments visually comparable to the Sun (apparent diameter 0.3°‑1.0°) naturally falls in the 5‑15 range due to the tidal disruption power law. Global myths record “nine” or “ten”—a natural result of this selection.

The present near‑side mare basins number about 8 (order of magnitude)—considering that some small impacts may have been covered by later volcanism, this count matches the “several to more than ten” expectation. The model does not require exactly “8,” only order‑of‑magnitude agreement.

2.4.2 Orbital Rendezvous Dynamics of Fragments with the Main Nucleus

After disruption, fragments share roughly the same orbital plane, but their specific orbital parameters (semi‑major axis a, eccentricity e, argument of periapsis ω) differ slightly due to their different initial positions and velocities at disruption.

Rendezvous mechanism: By Kepler’s third law, orbital period T ∝ a<sup>3/2</sup>. A small difference in semi‑major axis (Δa/a ~ 10⁻³‑10⁻²) leads to a period difference (ΔT/T ≈ 1.5 × Δa/a). If Δa/a ~ 0.01, then each orbit (≈12‑24 h) the fragment’s relative position to the main nucleus slides by ~1.5%. Over several to dozens of orbital periods, the fragment will approach the main nucleus and impact at closest approach.

Rendezvous relative velocity: If Δa/a ~ 10⁻³, relative speed is ~hundreds of m/s; if Δa/a ~ 10⁻², speed can reach 1‑3 km/s. This matches the energy needed for mare basin impacts.

Analogy with SL9: Comet Shoemaker‑Levy 9 was tidally disrupted by Jupiter in July 1992; the fragments orbited for about 2 years (~8 Jupiter orbital periods) before impacting Jupiter sequentially in July 1994. Near Earth, the orbital period is only ~1 day, so the impact sequence would complete within days to weeks, consistent with the mythological time scale (“Yi shot the ten suns, hitting nine”—implying continuous occurrence).

Visual realisation (Feature 3, §1.4): Fragments form a “string of pearls” in orbit, each illuminated by sunlight as an independent luminous body—“multiple suns in the sky.” Then, due to orbital period differences, fragments approach and merge with the main nucleus one by one; each merger produces a flash, and that light body disappears—“shooting the suns.” The ancients projected this process as hunting behaviour (“shooting”), essentially encoding the orbital rendezvous “collision‑disappearance” phenomenon using their familiar cognitive framework of combat and hunting.

2.4.3 Geometric Inevitability of Impacts: All Concentrated on the Near Side

Tidal locking: The main nucleus became tidally locked during the close flyby (synchronous rotation equals orbital period), so its near side always faces Earth.
Gravitational focusing: Fragments in similar orbits are gravitationally biased by Earth such that all impacts occur within ±60° of the near‑side meridian.
Physical inevitability: The far side is geometrically shielded and completely escapes.
This explains the most puzzling aspect of lunar dichotomy: 100% of major mare basins are on the near side.

2.4.4 Physics of a Single Impact (Target: Thick Ice Shell and Underlying Porous Matrix)

Impactors are pure ice (diameter 50‑200 km, density ~0.9 g/cm³); target is the main nucleus’s thick ice shell and underlying porous solid matrix.

Impact energy: ~10²⁴ J (per impact).
Energy dissipation: Most (>80%) goes into shock melting/vaporisation of the ice target and adiabatic compression/pore collapse of the porous matrix. Shock waves decay exponentially in porous media; only a tiny fraction is converted into far‑field seismic waves or high‑velocity ejecta.
Crater morphology: Extremely broad, shallow, flat‑bottomed, no central peak. The porous target cannot transmit the elastic rebound shock wave needed to form a central peak. Analogous to large impact craters on Earth in soft sediments, but amplified under lunar low gravity.
Explanation of ancient mare ages (3.3‑3.8 Ga): Mare basalts are mainly in near‑side basins, with ages mostly 3.9‑3.1 Ga (Zhou et al., 2010). These radiometric ages record the formation ages of the original solid debris constituting the porous matrix (from early Solar System planetesimal differentiation events), not the impact event itself. The 30,000‑year‑old impact only compacted the surface and stripped cover; it did not produce deep thermal metamorphism sufficient to reset the radiometric clock. Only the uppermost layers (cm‑m scale) may retain thermal signatures of the 30‑ka event.
2.5 Phase 3: Merger of Main Nucleus with Palaeo‑Moon—“Rocky Core Embedded in a Big Ice Ball”

2.5.1 Quantitative Estimate of Orbital Evolution

The cumulative momentum from multiple impacts can raise the main nucleus’s apogee from ~100,000 km to the altitude where it encounters the Palaeo‑Moon (150,000‑300,000 km). Momentum estimates (Appendix A2) show that with the right directions, changes of tens to hundreds of thousands of kilometres in apogee are possible.

2.5.2 Physical Mechanism of Merger (the “Ice Wrapping” Model)—The Model’s Most Critical Innovative Mechanical Correction

Merger scenario: The main nucleus (still wrapped in ~1000‑1500 km thick ice shell, total diameter ~4000‑5000 km, total mass ~10²³ kg, ice mass fraction ~60%‑70%) and the Palaeo‑Moon (diameter ~1500 km, dense rocky, mass ~10²¹‑10²² kg) meet on Earth‑orbit at a relative speed of 1‑3 km/s.

Why does it not shatter?—Perfect ice cushioning:

The Palaeo‑Moon first contacts the main nucleus’s hundreds‑to‑thousands‑kilometre‑thick pure ice shell, not the solid core.
Ice under high‑speed impact (>1 km/s) undergoes qualitative dynamic change: shock pressure causes melting and even vaporisation within nanoseconds to microseconds (ice shock melting threshold ≈0.5‑1 GPa, vaporisation ≈5‑10 GPa). The Palaeo‑Moon’s kinetic energy (~10²⁸ J) first melts/vaporises the ice along its path, creating a “melting tunnel.”
The Palaeo‑Moon, like a high‑speed thermal projectile, loses most of its speed after melting through the ice shell (dissipated) and eventually embeds softly into the porous solid matrix beneath the ice shell. There is no rock‑on‑rock rigid collision.
Re‑calculation and reinterpretation of the Sutton parameter (Q):

Nominal impact energy: E<sub>impact</sub> = ½ × 10²² × (2000)² = 2.0 × 10²⁸ J.
Nominal Q: Q = E<sub>impact</sub> / M<sub>total</sub> ≈ 1.8 × 10⁵ J/kg. In a “rock‑on‑rock” model, this is far above the fragmentation threshold (~10³ J/kg), predicting catastrophic disruption.
The model’s mechanical revolution: The Q‑value criterion does not apply when the target is a thick ice layer plus porous matrix. Ice’s latent heat of fusion (~3.3×10⁵ J/kg) and vaporisation (~2.83×10⁶ J/kg) are enormous energy sinks. Melting through 500 km of ice requires ~5×10²⁶ J; vaporising the same mass requires ~4×10²⁷ J—both comparable to the total impact energy (2×10²⁸ J). Thus, most kinetic energy is absorbed by phase changes, leaving little for mechanical fragmentation.
Post‑merger product—the “ice‑wrapped stone” composite:

The new Moon is now a giant ice sphere (diameter ~4000‑5000 km), containing a rocky core (the Palaeo‑Moon) near the far side, and a thin layer of porous matrix (cometary solid residue) beneath it.
Spatial topology: Since the Palaeo‑Moon approached from the outside (the side facing away from Earth) before merger, after merging it lies on the far side of the new composite, while the cometary ice‑dust material is concentrated on the near side.
Total mass ≈ original main nucleus mass + Palaeo‑Moon mass (~1.1×10²³ kg), with ice mass fraction as high as 60%‑70% (~6‑7×10²² kg).
2.6 Phase 4: Atmospheric Suspension‑Sedimentation Two‑Layer Model—“Mending the Sky” and “Chaos”

During the merger of the main nucleus with the Palaeo‑Moon, and during prior fragment impacts, huge amounts of material were injected into Earth’s atmosphere. These exogenous materials stratified physically according to particle size and altitude:

(a) Upper suspended layer (stratosphere/mesosphere, altitude 20‑80 km): Submicron dust and ice crystal aerosols suspended at this altitude for months to years. They scatter sunlight producing colourful airglow (wavelengths: green 557.7 nm, red 630.0 nm, yellow 589.0 nm), forming a global “five‑colour luminous curtain”—recorded as “Nüwa smelted five‑coloured stones to mend the azure sky” (physical realisation of Feature 4, §1.4). High‑altitude discharges (red sprites, blue jets) caused by ice crystal friction made the sky appear “chaotic with coloured light.”

(b) Lower sedimentation layer (troposphere, altitude 0‑20 km): Larger ice crystals and raindrops fell continuously over weeks to months, producing global torrential rain and snow. Low‑altitude thick clouds and precipitation columns obscured visibility, blurring the boundary between sky and earth—“heaven and earth chaotic like a chicken egg.” The upper layer’s clearing occurred mainly through rainout, so “mending the sky” (thinning of the suspended layer) and “flood” (precipitation) overlapped in time and were causally interlinked.

(c) Climatic consequence—triggering and intensification of the Last Glacial Maximum: The upper suspended layer reflected much solar radiation, dropping global average temperature by ~5‑10°C. Combined with the ice‑albedo positive feedback, this intensified and prolonged the Last Glacial Maximum by about 10,000 years.

Trigger mechanism of the LGM: The model further proposes that the ~30,000‑year‑old cometary capture event was not merely an intensifier of the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM, ≈26,500‑19,000 BP), but likely its direct trigger. Conventional orbital forcing (Milankovitch cycles) cannot explain the abrupt acceleration of the LGM; the comet event, through triple forcing—atmospheric dust shading (instant cooling), massive water vapour forming high‑latitude ice increasing albedo, and freshwater injection disrupting thermohaline circulation—pushed the climate system out of the orbital‑driven gradual equilibrium into an extreme cold peak dominated by exogenous mass injection.

2.7 Phase 5: Disappearance of the Cometary Tail—“The Heavenly Pillar Broke”

At initial capture, the main nucleus carried a strong coma/tail, forming a vertical luminous pillar from horizon to zenith. As the ice shell was consumed, the orbit receded, and volatiles dissipated, the tail gradually vanished—“the heavenly pillar broke.” This requires no explanation as physical structural failure, only as the disappearance of a visual structure.

2.8 Phase 6 (Core Innovation): Sublimation‑Driven Orbital Migration—The Physical Reality of “Separation of Heaven and Earth”

This is the most core mechanical mechanism in the model for explaining the “Separation of Heaven and Earth” myth and the origin of the lunar orbit.

2.8.1 Fate of the “Big Ice Ball” in Low Orbit

The merged new Moon is a giant ice ball of diameter ~4000‑5000 km (still with a substantial ice shell), initially at an orbital altitude of ~20,000‑50,000 km (geocentric distance ~30,000‑60,000 km). It faces two powerful heat sources:

Residual internal heat from merger: the impact thermal energy (~10²⁸ J) from the Palaeo‑Moon melting through the ice shell is trapped inside the ice, continuously heating surrounding ice to hundreds or even thousands of degrees (locally).
Intense solar radiation in near‑Earth orbit: at only tens of thousands of kilometres from Earth, solar irradiance is (384,000/50,000)² ≈ 59 times to (384,000/30,000)² ≈ 164 times that at the present Earth‑Moon distance. The per‑unit‑area solar energy input is vastly increased.
These two heat sources together drive a large‑scale sublimation process lasting thousands of years. The ice surface temperature rises above ‑50°C to 0°C or more; in vacuum, water ice sublimates directly into vapour, escaping at thermal speeds (≈0.5‑1 km/s).

2.8.2 Sublimation‑Driven Orbital Expansion (The Power of Angular Momentum Conservation)

This is the decisive physical equation explaining “Separation of Heaven and Earth.”

Assuming total angular momentum of the Earth‑Moon system is conserved (no significant external torque):

L = M ⋅ R² ⋅ ω = M ⋅ √(GM<sub>E</sub> ⋅ R) = constant
From this, the relationship between orbital radius R and system mass M is:

R ∝ 1 / M²
Physical evolution:

Initial state: After merger, total mass M<sub>0</sub> ≈ 1.1 × 10²³ kg (ice mass ~6 × 10²² kg), initial orbital radius R<sub>0</sub> ≈ 5 × 10⁴ km (50,000 km).
Sublimation process: Over millennia, huge amounts of water ice sublimate and escape at high speed (~0.5‑1 km/s). As mass is lost (like a rocket recoil), the remaining body’s mass M decreases. Some vapour escapes into interplanetary space, some is captured by Earth’s gravity (see §2.9).
Orbital expansion: Due to angular momentum conservation, when mass drops from 1.1×10²³ kg to the present Moon’s 7.3×10²² kg (loss ≈3.7×10²² kg, ≈34% of original):
R<sub>final</sub> = R<sub>0</sub> × (M<sub>0</sub> / M<sub>final</sub>)² = 5×10⁴ × (1.1×10²³ / 7.3×10²²)² ≈ 5×10⁴ × (1.51)² ≈ 1.14×10⁵ km
This yields ~114,000 km—already about one‑third of the present orbit (384,000 km).

Supplementary driving force: Tidal recession (dR/dt ∝ R<sup>‑6</sup>) becomes inefficient at larger distances, but at low orbits (50,000‑100,000 km) it is extremely efficient. After sublimation pushes the orbit from 50,000 km to 114,000 km, tidal dissipation takes over and can continue pushing to 384,000 km. Sublimation drove the early major expansion (50,000 → 114,000 km); tides drove the later fine adjustment (114,000 → 384,000 km).

2.8.3 Visual and Hydrological Effects of Sublimation Ejecta

Visual effect (“Separation of Heaven and Earth”): As the ice sublimates, the Moon’s apparent diameter shrinks from an initial 4°‑10° (filling half the sky) to today’s 0.5°. Over multiple generations, observers witnessed this process, recording it as “Heaven rose one zhang each day, earth thickened one zhang each day”—an encoding of the intergenerational cumulative decrease in apparent diameter (§1.3 “visual scaling”). Simultaneously, the reflectance dropped drastically due to ice loss, turning the Moon from a bright “mini‑Sun” to its present grey appearance.
Hydrological effect (“Heavenly water” supply): The ejected water vapour did not all escape. About 20%‑40% was captured by Earth’s gravity, condensed at high altitude, and fell as torrential rain, contributing significantly to the global flood (combined with §2.9).
2.8.4 Structural Correspondence with the “Separation of Heaven and Earth” Myth

The universal narrative structure of the “Separation of Heaven and Earth” motif is: Heaven and Earth were originally very close (or even connected), then some force “lifted” or “pushed” them apart, and the distance grew ever larger. The Chinese Pangu story “Heaven rose one zhang each day, earth thickened one zhang each day, Pangu grew one zhang each day” precisely corresponds to the gradual shrinking of the Moon’s apparent diameter over generations; the Greek separation of Uranus and Gaia, and the Norse creation from Ymir’s body, can all be seen as cultural projections of this orbital expansion event.

