These narratives may partly reflect the literary structural need to establish the world framework before placing celestial bodies. However, three geographically isolated civilisations independently producing the same narrative structure (Sun and Moon appear after heaven and earth) gains a natural physical explanation in this model: before the event, the Palaeo‑Moon was too dim and insignificant to be culturally recognised as “Moon”; after the event, the New Moon became visually extremely prominent (apparent diameter 4°‑10°, 8‑20 times larger), and had to be incorporated into creation narratives as a new element requiring explanation.

3.3 Post‑Event Archaeological Shift—The “Explosion” of Celestial Worship

3.3.1 The Abrupt Neolithic Transition

After the event, during the Neolithic (starting ~12,000 BP), celestial motifs appear massively worldwide:

Yangshao culture (≈7000‑5000 BP) painted pottery with sun and moon motifs
Stonehenge (≈5000 BP) astronomical alignments
Egyptian pyramids (≈4500 BP) correlated with constellations
Sumerian lunar calendar (≈6000 BP)
Mesoamerican Olmec (≈3500 BP) astronomical traditions
The transition from “unequivocal celestial depictions extremely rare” in the Late Palaeolithic to the “explosion of celestial worship” in the Neolithic—around 12,000 BP—roughly coincides with the model’s predicted window for institutionalisation of disaster memory (~12,000 BP onwards, coinciding with agricultural settlement and the dawn of civilisation).

3.3.2 Explanation: Institutionalisation of Disaster Memory

The model interprets this transition as the natural result of disaster memory being fixed and deified through oral tradition and ritual. The nearly 20,000‑year‑long astronomical drama (30‑12 ka)—multiple suns, successive impact flashes, airglow, super‑tides, global floods—left deep cultural imprints on survivors. When climate stabilised and agriculture began ~12,000 years ago, these memories, transmitted orally for tens of thousands of years, were ritualised, mythologised, and institutionalised, giving rise to global celestial worship and astronomical traditions.

3.4 Testable Archaeological Predictions

If the model holds, we should observe:

Unequivocal depictions of a large satellite (Moon) in Late Palaeolithic (≈40‑20 ka) rock art should be extremely rare and with contested reliable dating—because the “Moon” (Palaeo‑Moon) then had an apparent diameter of only 0.15°‑0.3°, too low in visual prominence.
The global explosion of celestial worship should not predate ~12,000 BP—because the New Moon’s visual prominence increased dramatically (apparent diameter 4°‑10°), and disaster memory institutionalisation made celestial bodies cultural foci.
Middle‑period sites (≈30‑12 ka) may contain abstract symbols related to “multiple suns,” “vertical light pillars,” and “colourful skies”—direct attempts by eyewitnesses to record the astronomical drama.
Future more precise dating and rock‑art semiotic studies can test these assumptions more rigorously.
