4.1 Independence of Time Anchoring

The model’s time framework is not supported by a single chain, but by convergence of three independent chains:

Astronomical chain (independent of human records): Scholz’s Star flyby time (Mamajek et al., 2015) + debris travel time (Keplerian mechanics) = arrival window ~35‑32 ka. This chain does not depend on any Earth‑based evidence.
Geological chain (independent of astronomical calculations and human records): Ice core anomalies, deep‑sea turbidites, MWP‑1A, Younger Dryas—these are dated radiometrically, independently of astronomical calculations.
Archaeological/mythological chain (independent of the first two): Palaeolithic “moonless” observations, Neolithic explosion of celestial worship, cross‑cultural “Sun and Moon born after creation” motif—their chronology is determined by archaeological stratigraphy and ¹⁴C dating.
Each chain has its own independent error range, yet they converge on the ~30‑12 ka window. This triple independent verification distinguishes the model’s time frame from any single‑chain argument.

4.2 Fidelity and Time Span of Oral Memory

When the events occurred (32‑12 ka), writing had not been invented. The earliest writing systems (Sumerian cuneiform ~3500 BCE, Egyptian hieroglyphs ~3200 BCE, Chinese oracle bones ~1200 BCE) appeared nearly 10,000 years after the events.

But writing is not the only medium of memory. Ethnographic evidence shows that oral traditions can retain remarkable fidelity in non‑literate societies:

Australian Aboriginal oral traditions accurately describe post‑glacial coastline retreat ~10,000 years ago, matching geological reconstructions (Nunn & Reid, 2016), proving that oral systems can transmit critical environmental information across generations.
The global flood myth’s core structure—“waters from heaven and fountains of the deep burst forth”—is consistent across all surveyed civilisations, suggesting a common encoding of a real physical event.
Therefore, the ~25,000‑year oral phase from the event (~30 ka) to the invention of writing (~5500 BP) does not necessarily preclude faithful transmission—human language and narrative systems have evolved sufficient redundancy and structure to convey catastrophic event information.

