7. Explanation of the Archaeological Discontinuity

7.1 Palaeolithic → Neolithic Shift in Celestial Worship

Based on the time anchors in Chapters 3‑4, this shift can be explained within a precise timeline:

Palaeolithic (40‑20 ka): The Palaeo‑Moon was too small and dim (apparent diameter 0.15°‑0.3°) to be visually prominent in rock art. No global astronomical drama occurred. Unequivocal celestial depictions are extremely rare.
Event period (32‑12 ka): A ~20,000‑year‑long astronomical catastrophe—multiple suns, successive impact flashes, airglow, super‑tides, global floods—left deep cultural imprints on survivors. The New Moon’s apparent diameter (4°‑10°, 8‑20 times larger) was visually transformative. Eyewitnesses encoded these phenomena into oral narratives, transmitted across generations.
Neolithic (from ~12 ka): As climate stabilised and agriculture began, descendants institutionalised and deified these disaster memories, giving rise to global celestial worship and astronomical traditions. This is the natural result of disaster memory being fixed through oral tradition and ritual.
7.2 The Universal Motif “Sun and Moon Born After Heaven and Earth”

China (Pangu’s eyes), Greece (Selene as second‑generation deity), and Norse (gods created Sun and Moon after heaven and earth) all share the narrative structure that Sun and Moon appeared only after heaven and earth stabilised. This is fully consistent with the model: before the event, the Palaeo‑Moon was too dim to be culturally recognised as “Moon”; after the event, the New Moon became extremely bright and large, becoming the protagonist of myth.

