10. Conclusion

This paper proposes the Comet Capture‑Disruption‑Merger‑Sublimation Hypothesis, with the following core conclusions:

(1) Myth as physical constraint. The four visual features of global creation myths—all‑covering dome, vertical light pillar, sequential falls, colourful canopy—constitute a unique “astronomical fingerprint.” After systematically excluding asteroid impacts, supervolcanoes, supernovae, etc., only a super‑comet nucleus passing extremely close to the Roche limit can simultaneously produce all four. The mythological data themselves are hard constraints filtering physical models.

(2) Triple time anchoring. Three independent chains—astronomical (Scholz’s Star flyby ~70 ka + debris travel ~30‑40 ka), geological (MWP‑1A ~14.5 ka, Younger Dryas ~12.8‑11.5 ka), and archaeological/mythological (Palaeolithic “moonless” → Neolithic explosion of celestial worship)—converge on the ~32‑12 ka window.

(3) Full physical chain. The Palaeo‑Moon (diameter 1000‑2000 km) provided billions of years of tidal braking; Scholz’s Star perturbed the Oort Cloud ~70 ka; the comet nucleus underwent tidal disruption below the Roche limit ~30 ka; fragments impacted the near side to form maria; the main nucleus merged with the Palaeo‑Moon at low speed (the Palaeo‑Moon melted through the thick ice shell and embedded in the porous matrix); the merged body’s thick ice shell sublimated massively under heat, driving orbital migration via angular momentum conservation (R ∝ 1/M²) from ~50,000 km to ~380,000 km—the physical reality of “Separation of Heaven and Earth”; impact and sublimation water vapour totalled 10²⁰‑10²¹ kg, released in two phases—immediate rainfall combined with super‑tides created the “Great Flood” memory, half stored in ice sheets and released ~14.5 ka; the cometary injection of matter and energy triggered abrupt global cooling, pushing the Last Glacial Maximum to its peak.

(4) Observational explanations and falsifiable predictions. The model independently explains lunar dichotomy, the absence of central peaks in maria, regolith characteristics, the co‑existence of ancient basaltic ages with young surface structures, Earth‑Moon compositional similarity, the fossil record of day length, and the Palaeolithic‑Neolithic cultural break. Exclusive predictions distinguishing it from all competing hypotheses include: a ~30‑ka quenched glassy top layer in maria, polar water ice D/H close to cometary values, Δ¹⁷O >0.05‰ between near and far sides, and a cometary material anomaly layer at ~27 ka in global strata.

The Moon is a two‑hemisphere composite—its far hemisphere is the Palaeo‑Moon, its near hemisphere is cometary porous residue. Our ancestors encoded this ~15,000‑year‑long astronomical drama as creation myths, transmitted across generations. The history of human civilisation is the history of moving from “observation and encoding” to “understanding and decoding.”

