Appendix A: Key Order‑of‑Magnitude Estimates

A1 Minimum Tidal Braking Mass of the Palaeo‑Moon

Tidal dissipation power scales with the square of satellite mass and inversely with the sixth power of orbital radius:

τ ∝ m² / R⁶
Equate the Palaeo‑Moon’s tidal braking effect to that of the present Moon:

(m<sub>p</sub> / m<sub>now</sub>)² ∝ (R<sub>p</sub> / R<sub>now</sub>)⁶
Taking R<sub>p</sub> = 2×10⁷ m (safe orbit outside Roche limit), R<sub>now</sub> = 3.84×10⁸ m:

m<sub>p</sub> ≈ 7.3×10²² / 7140 ≈ 1.0×10¹⁹ kg
This corresponds to a diameter of ~180‑270 km. Considering orbital decay and cumulative effects over billions of years, applying a safety factor of ×5‑10 gives 5×10¹⁹‑1×10²⁰ kg (diameter ~300‑500 km). The model’s 10²¹‑10²² kg (diameter 1000‑2000 km) far exceeds the requirement, providing ample tidal braking.

A2 Impact Cumulative Momentum and Orbital Change

One large fragment impact (fragment mass ~10¹⁷ kg, relative velocity ~3 km/s):

Δp = m<sub>f</sub> × v<sub>rel</sub> ≈ 10¹⁷ × 3000 = 3×10²⁰ kg⋅m/s
Total (8‑10 effective impacts):

Δp<sub>total</sub> ≥ 2.4×10²¹ kg⋅m/s
Main nucleus mass M ≈ 10²³ kg, resulting velocity change:

Δv ≈ Δp / M ≈ 0.02 - 0.05 m/s
On a timescale of months‑years, each perigee velocity perturbation accumulates, potentially raising apogee by tens to hundreds of thousands of kilometres. Exact values depend on timing and direction, requiring N‑body simulations.

A3 Energy Budget for Palaeo‑Moon Melting Through Ice Shell (Feasibility of Merger)

Palaeo‑Moon impact kinetic energy E<sub>k</sub> = 2.0×10²⁸ J.

Energy required to melt through 500 km of ice (heating ice from ‑100°C to 0°C and melting):

Specific heat of ice c<sub>p</sub> ≈ 2.1×10³ J/(kg·K), heating 200 K: 4.2×10⁵ J/kg
Latent heat of fusion L<sub>f</sub> ≈ 3.3×10⁵ J/kg
Total: 7.5×10⁵ J/kg
Cross‑sectional area of melting path ≈ π × (750 km)² ≈ 1.77×10¹² m²
Volume of 500 km ice = 8.85×10¹⁷ m³, mass = 8.0×10¹⁷ kg
Required energy = 6.0×10²³ J
This is only 0.003% of the impact energy (2.0×10²⁸ J). Even if the path were 10 times larger and part of the ice vaporised, the required energy would remain far smaller than the total kinetic energy. Therefore, the Palaeo‑Moon melting through the ice shell is energetically easily feasible.

A4 Sublimation‑Driven Orbital Migration Calculation

Initial: M<sub>0</sub> = 1.1×10²³ kg, R<sub>0</sub> = 5.0×10⁴ km
Final: M<sub>f</sub> = 7.3×10²² kg

From angular momentum conservation R ∝ 1/M²:

R<sub>f</sub> = R<sub>0</sub> × (M<sub>0</sub> / M<sub>f</sub>)² = 5.0×10⁴ × (1.1/0.73)² = 5.0×10⁴ × 2.27 = 1.135×10⁵ km
Sublimation‑driven expansion pushes the Moon from 50,000 km to ~114,000 km. Tidal recession then takes over from 114,000 km to 384,000 km. The tidal timescale via standard tidal evolution equations is efficient at lower altitudes (<150,000 km), and can complete the remaining recession in ~10,000‑20,000 years.

